03811nam a22004815i 9780226041490DE-B159720210324034602.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210324t20211995ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260414907 a10.7208/97802260414902doi  a(DE-B1597)575558  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHQ1075.5.U6 -- B43 1995eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.0973a305.3/09731 aBederman, Gail, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManliness and Civilization :bA Cultural History of Gender and Race in the United States, 1880-1917 /cGail Bederman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (322 p.) :b12 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWomen in Culture and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Remaking Manhood through Race arid "Civilization" -- t2. "The White Man's Civilization on Trial": Ida B. Wells, Representations of Lynching, and Northern Middle-Class Manhood -- t3. "Teaching Our Sons to Do What 'We Have Been Teaching the Savages to Avoid": G. Stanley Hall, Racial Recapitulation, and the Neurasthenic Paradox -- t4. "Not to Sex-But to Race!" Charlotte Perkins Gilman, Civilized Anglo-Saxon Womanhood, and the Return of the Primitive Rapist -- t5. Theodore Roosevelt: Manhood, Nation, and "Civilization" -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen former heavyweight champion Jim Jeffries came out of retirement on the fourth of July, 1910 to fight current black heavywight champion Jack Johnson in Reno, Nevada, he boasted that he was doing it "for the sole purpose of proving that a white man is better than a negro." Jeffries, though, was trounced. Whites everywhere rioted. The furor, Gail Bederman demonstrates, was part of two fundamental and volatile national obsessions: manhood and racial dominance. In turn-of-the-century America, cultural ideals of manhood changed profoundly, as Victorian notions of self-restrained, moral manliness were challenged by ideals of an aggressive, overtly sexualized masculinity. Bederman traces this shift in values and shows how it brought together two seemingly contradictory ideals: the unfettered virility of racially "primitive" men and the refined superiority of "civilized" white men. Focusing on the lives and works of four very different Americans—Theodore Roosevelt, educator G. Stanley Hall, Ida B. Wells, and Charlotte Perkins Gilman—she illuminates the ideological, cultural, and social interests these ideals came to serve.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mrz 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aStimpson, Catharine R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226041490423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226041490.jpg  a978-3-11-066785-1  UChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aGBV-deGruyter-alles